<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Sun 7 Nov 2004
From: Pablo Nart <pablo11@hotpop.com>

Bluetongue situation in Spain
-----------------------------
It seems that the situation regarding the Bluetongue (BT) epidemic in
peninsular Spain is not getting better. The 2 new outbreaks, reported on 5
Nov 2004 in OIE follow-up report No. 3
<http://oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_20.HTM#Sec5>,
in Coin and Tolox (Malaga province), are about 25 km apart and more than
100 km east of the 1st cases reported in Jimena de la Frontera (Cadiz
province).
Perhaps more worrying is the information included in OIE's follow-up report
No. 2 of 29 Oct 2004
<http://oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_21.HTM#Sec5>
describing 2 new outbreaks in different localities situated more than 100
km apart in Extremadura, and 450 km northwest of the 1st outbreak reported
in Cadiz on 13 Oct 2004. The border with Portugal is not very far away,
there is active movement of animals between countries, and no geographical
barriers to stop the wind-borne vectors.
The presence of _Culicoides imicola_ has been reported all over the western
half of the Iberic peninsula, as far as Braganca in northern Portugal.
The last press report, originally in Spanish, reports the detection of one
clinical case in a calf, in Navarra, not far from the French border.
Reportedly, this case has been confirmed by the central laboratories
(Laboratorio Central de Veterinaria de Algete, Ministry of Agriculture).
In the same area, serosurvellance has detected 3 other positive cases among
1124 sampled cattle. No BT-positive animals were found amongst the 895
tested sheep. According to the report, _Culicoides imicola_ is not present
in Navarra.
Tracing of animals linked to the index case in Cadiz has led to the
detection of seropositive animals in other areas of mainland Spain, such as
Valencia, Salamanca, Zamora, Murcia, Malaga, and Cordoba, the press report
concludes.
References:
1. Using climate data to map the potential distribution of _Culicoides
imicola_ (Diptera: Ceratopogonidae) in Europe. Wittmann EJ, Mellor PS and
Baylis M in Rev. sci. tech. Off. int. Epiz. 2001 20(3):731-740.
<http://www.oie.int/eng/publicat/rt/2003/WITTMANN.PDF>
2. Spatial distribution of Culicoides species in Portugal in relation to
the transmission of African horse sickness and bluetongue viruses. Capela
R, Purse BV, Pena I, Wittman EJ, Margarita Y, Capela M, Romao L, Mellor PS
& Baylis M. Department of Biology & Geology, Universidade da Madeira,
Portugal. Med Vet Entomol. 2003 17(2):165-77 PMID: 12823834
--
Pablo Nart
<pablo11@hotpop.com>
